<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Where should I put my primary keyword?</strong></p>
<p>In the title tag, meta description, H1, URL, first 100 words, at least one H2, body content (3-5 times per 1,000 words), image alt text, internal link anchor text, and conclusion.</p>
<p><strong>How many times should I use a keyword in an article?</strong></p>
<p>Use the primary keyword 3-5 times per 1,000 words. Use secondary keywords 1-2 times each. Add LSI keywords naturally throughout.</p>
<p><strong>Is keyword density still important?</strong></p>
<p>Not as a strict formula. Focus on natural usage rather than exact percentages. A density of 1-2% is a safe guideline.</p>
<p><strong>Should I use exact-match keywords only?</strong></p>
<p>No. Use variations, synonyms, and LSI keywords. Google understands semantic relationships between words.</p>
<p><strong>Can I rank without using the keyword in the title?</strong></p>
<p>Sometimes, but it is much harder. The title tag is the strongest on-page signal. Always include the primary keyword in the title.</p>
<p><strong>What is the difference between H1 and title tag?</strong></p>
<p>The title tag appears in search results and browser tabs. The H1 appears on the page itself. They can be similar but should not be identical. The title tag can include modifiers for clicks. The H1 should be descriptive.</p>
